	<td bgcolor="#000000" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" > <b>Taunt Skill</b></font>
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" >I've always wondered why I had a taunt "skill" that went up with my lvls.  If taunt were based totally upon the RNG and a pass/fail system, wouldn't this make my skill in the ability superfluous?  This thread go me thinking that a taunt skill would work and make sense if tuanting actually added an amount of hate, with your "skill" being the modifier, much like increasing your skill in defense will increase your AC.  With that in mind perhaps the results of taunt could be broken into three categories.<br />
<br />
1.  Taunt failure - self explanatory<br />
2.  Taunt success - a fixed amount of hate is added, this acquired through a base amount determined by your lvl + an amount determined by your taunting skill.<br />
3.  Critical taunt - you are automatically moved to the top of the aggro list.  <br />
<br />
Anyways, just a thought.  Good thread so far, thanks for the original post Brutul.  I sure hope this doesn't mean I'm gonna have to go back to mashing my taunt button though......<br />
<br />
Khazzuz<br />
55 Warrior on Povar</font></p>
	
